<div class="prose">

<p>A water-systems tutor and <strong>Unit 5's broad-scope science partner</strong> — used in Blocks 1–4 (water systems learning) and Blocks 6–9 (case-specific hydrology + Position Paper drafting). It helps you reason about water cycles, residence times, watersheds, aquifers, and water quality — and translate that physical hydrology into the dynamics of your chosen case (Cauvery, Indus, Colorado, Nile, Mekong, Aral, Cooum, Bangalore). It holds one line firmly: it helps with the science underneath the dispute, not the advocacy on top of it — the advocacy is your <a href="/units/unit-5/assessment-water-stakeholders/">Position Paper</a>. For perspective-taking it hands you to the <a href="/ai-partners/stakeholder-voice/">Stakeholder Voice</a>.</p>

{% include "partials/partner-launch.njk" %}

<h2>How to use this partner</h2>

<p>Name your case and the specific aspect you're analyzing — the technical hydrology, the allocation politics, or the climate context. The Hydrologist connects technical concepts to policy stakes (why residence time matters for the Cauvery; why aquifer depletion matters for Bangalore) and will make you choose between <strong>physical scarcity</strong> (not enough water) and <strong>economic scarcity</strong> (not enough infrastructure) — most "water shortage" framings collapse the two, and the solutions differ.</p>

<p>Two prompts you can paste in to get started:</p>

<ul>
  <li><em>"I'm working on the Cauvery dispute. Help me build the Background section's hydrology: what's the supply, what's the demand, and what does monsoon variability do to both?"</em></li>
  <li><em>"Is Bangalore's water crisis physical scarcity or economic scarcity? Walk me through how I'd tell the difference from the evidence."</em></li>
</ul>

<h2>Opening message</h2>

<blockquote>"Hi — I'm the Hydrologist. What water case are you working on, and what specifically do you want to understand about its hydrology? I can help with the physical water systems (cycles, watersheds, aquifers, quality) and with how those systems connect to allocation disputes. I'll let you handle the stakeholder advocacy yourself."</blockquote>

<h2>Example exchange — what working looks like</h2>

<table>
  <thead>
    <tr><th>You</th><th>The Hydrologist</th></tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr>
      <td>Is Karnataka being unfair to Tamil Nadu in the Cauvery dispute?</td>
      <td>That's an advocacy question — and an important one — but I can't help you decide it. What I can help you with is the hydrology underneath it. So let me ask: when you say "unfair," what specifically are you measuring? The total annual flow Karnataka releases at the inter-state boundary? The seasonal timing of those releases (Tamil Nadu's delta needs water during the <em>kharif</em> growing season, not just total volume)? Karnataka's own monsoon failures in the upstream catchment? Or the long-term aquifer depletion under both states that no surface-water-only treaty can address? Each of those framings produces a different answer to your question. Once you've picked one, I can help you reason about the hydrologic evidence.</td>
    </tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<h2>Watch out for</h2>

<p>Pressed for a verdict — "just tell me who's right" — the Hydrologist can drift into advocacy. That's your Position Paper's job, not its. If you notice it taking sides, redirect: <em>"back to the hydrology — what does the evidence show under my framing?"</em> and it should hand the advocacy back to you.</p>

<p>Also watch for outdated numbers. Cauvery allocation figures in particular have changed repeatedly through tribunal rulings and Supreme Court verdicts — a confident-sounding figure may predate the 2018 verdict. Verify any specific water-quantity claim against tribunal documents, recent rulings, or government reports before citing it. Catching one is the "one thing the AI got wrong" gate on the <a href="/units/unit-5/assessment-water-stakeholders/">Position Paper</a> rubric.</p>

<h2>Before you go — documentation</h2>

<p>At the end of a substantive Hydrologist conversation, the partner will remind you:</p>

<blockquote>"Before you go — note in your <a href="/foundations/ai-documentation-protocol/">AI Documentation</a>: which hydrological concept did our conversation help you understand more precisely than you would have on your own? And what's one numerical or factual claim I made that you should verify against a tribunal document, court ruling, government report, or peer-reviewed source?"</blockquote>

